data.current_description:
This endpoint gets called after the triggering the authorize flow.

Callback links need a state and code parameter to verify the validity of the request.
data.description_suggestion: Processes the OAuth authorization callback after a consumer completes authentication with a connector. This endpoint validates the authorization request using the state and code parameters to ensure security and prevent CSRF attacks. Upon successful validation, the connection is established and the consumer is redirected back to your application. Required parameters: state (for CSRF protection) and code (authorization code from the OAuth provider).

data.current_description:
__In most cases the authorize link is provided in the ``/connections`` endpoint. Normally you don't need to manually generate these links.__

Use this endpoint to authenticate a user with a connector. It will return a 301 redirect to the downstream connector endpoints.

Auth links will have a state parameter included to verify the validity of the request. This is the url your users will use to activate OAuth supported integration providers.

Vault handles the complete Authorization Code Grant Type Flow for you and will redirect you to the dynamic redirect uri you have appended to the url in case this is missing the default redirect uri you have configured for your Unify application.
data.summary_suggestion: Initiate OAuth authorization flow for connector
data.description_suggestion: Initiates the OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code Grant Type flow for a consumer to authenticate with a connector. Returns a 301 redirect to the connector's authorization endpoint. Includes a state parameter for request validation. Vault handles the complete OAuth flow and redirects to the specified redirect URI (or your configured default) upon completion. This endpoint is typically called automatically via the /connections endpoint.
data.reasoning: Original summary 'Authorize' is too vague for AI agents. Description is verbose and unclear about the actual return behavior and when to use this endpoint. Improved summary specifies OAuth authorization initiation. Enhanced description clarifies the OAuth flow type, redirect behavior, state parameter purpose, and when this endpoint should be used, making it more actionable for AI agents.

data.current_description:
__In most cases the authorize link is provided in the ``/connections`` endpoint. Normally you don't need to manually generate these links.__

Use this endpoint to revoke an existing OAuth connector.

Auth links will have a state parameter included to verify the validity of the request. This is the url your users will use to activate OAuth supported integration providers.

Vault handles the complete revoke flow for you and will redirect you to the dynamic redirect uri you have appended to the url.
data.description_suggestion: Revokes an existing OAuth connection for a consumer with a connector, invalidating the stored credentials and access tokens. Returns a 301 redirect to the specified redirect URI (or your configured default). Includes a state parameter for request validation. Vault handles the complete revocation flow and credential cleanup. This endpoint is typically called automatically via the /connections endpoint.
data.reasoning: Summary lacks specificity about OAuth context. Description contains misleading information about 'auth links' and 'activate OAuth' which is inconsistent with revocation purpose. Enhanced summary clarifies OAuth revocation. Improved description explains the actual effect (credential invalidation), redirect behavior, and clarifies this is for revoking existing connections, not activating new ones.
